oints: even when recovery data is present again, stable names, URLs, tokens, group bindings, and external references often still drift and require a separate repair pass.\\n- Batch 017 shows the next shift after identifier repair: recovered systems often still need fresh trust material or permission replay before they are truly usable, including disabled key versions, invalidated runner tokens, staged app access, BYOK reauthorization, and manually replayed CI secrets.\\n- Batch 018 shows the next shift after credential repair: issuing fresh trust is still insufficient until old cookies, old SSO sessions, old PATs, and delayed revocation windows are explicitly flushed and allowed to converge.\\n- Batch 019 shows the next shift after stale-trust cleanup: vendors increasingly expose fragmented inspection surfaces for what trust is still alive, such as last-used factors, recent devices, active PAT inventories, runner status tables, service-account auth times, and recently used CI auth tokens, but rarely provide a single \\\"clean baseline reached\\\" verdict.\\n- Batch 020 shows the next shift after residual-trust inventory: the key product surface is now the exception backlog itself, including pending approvals, inactive or half-offboarded identities, policy-mismatch CSVs, and agent-state lanes that still require a named next action.\\n- Batch 021 shows the next shift after visible exception backlogs: vendors are increasingly attaching countdown semantics to unresolved residue, including 7-day, 14-day, 30-day, 6-month, and 1-year windows that silently expire, auto-remove, unauthorize, or force token replacement.\\n- Batch 022 shows the next shift after countdown semantics: vendors are now explicit about the exact lane after the timer fires, including failed invitations, auto-removed runners, suspended-but-reinstatable identities, unrecoverable accounts, expired-but-seat-consuming invites, and unauthorized agents that free licenses.\\n- Batch 023 shows the next shift after reentry gates: the decisive question is now what state actually survives the way back in, including licenses, shares, team bindings, forks, tokens, app grants, and build artifacts.\\n- The strongest continuity split is no longer only identity-vs-deletion. It is identity continuity versus collaboration continuity versus payload continuity, and vendors now document different inheritance rules for each layer.\\n- The emerging editorial story is shifting from reversible delete to recovery-completeness operations: conflict checks, reindex progress, audit-backed rebuild manifests, compliance logs, remote archive sync, mount proofs, ready endpoints, diff exports, residual-trust inventories, and cleanup exception queues are becoming the real signal surfaces.\\n- The next editorial layer is no longer just \\\"what terminal state will the platform force if operators do nothing before the timer expires?\\\" but also \\\"how can operators prove a reopened path inherited original lineage instead of becoming a rebuilt substitute?\\\"\\n\\n## Next\\n\\n- Produce batch 024 as a narrow post-recovery inherited-versus-rebuilt proof-surface pass.\\n- Center batch 024 on:\\n  - official surfaces that show whether a restored path is marked as reinstated, recreated, relabeled, or manually rebuilt,\\n  - audit, membership, or admin pages that let operators prove lineage continuity after reactivation or reprovision,\\n  - repo, team, token, artifact, or access indicators that expose inherited state versus missing secondary metadata,\\n  - and vendor proof surfaces that distinguish \\\"same object returned\\\" from \\\"new object created with partial carryover.\\\"\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n/Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-signal-radar-runner/logs/iteration_018.log:17:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_7\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' ../memory/CONTEXT.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Theme Signal Radar Context\\n\\n## Fact\\n\\n- Shared workspace:\\n  - `workspace/theme-exploration-shared` points to `/Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-exploration-shared`.\\n  - Write output only to `signals/`.\\n- Signal standard:\\n  - Separate facts, inferences, and recommendations.\\n  - Preserve source URLs for every factual claim.\\n  - Prefer primary or near-primary sources.\\n  - Mark confidence as high, medium, or low.\\n  - Do not invent missing facts; weak sourcing requires an evidence-gap note.\\n- 2026-05-04: created `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-04-signal-radar-batch-001.md` with 31 source-backed signals across AI agents, coding agents, AI devtools, AI infra/pricing, creative AI, local-first tools, open-source productization, and content automation.\\n- 2026-05-04: created `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-05-signal-radar-batch-002.md` with 12 protocol/distribution signals on MCP, A2A, ACP, managed endpoints, registry surfaces, and IDE support.\\n- 2026-05-04: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-06-signal-radar-batch-003.md` with 10 control-plane signals across approvals, auth, quotas, sandboxing, registry trust, and tool-surface minimization.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-07-signal-radar-batch-004.md` with 9 observability/accountability signals across traces, eval loops, compliance logs, usage metering, session logs, and post-action review.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-08-signal-radar-batch-005.md` with 9 change-control/provenance signals across frozen snapshots, action diffs, model pinning, immutable revisions, signed attestations, verified catalogs, and plugin signing/review.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-09-signal-radar-batch-006.md` with 8 revocation/rollback signals across model retirement, attestation deletion, undeploy semantics, uninstall residue, plugin hide/remove flows, token revoke, and app-surface disable paths.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-10-signal-radar-batch-007.md` with 9 expiry/hygiene signals across Realtime token TTLs, vector-store expiry and cleanup lag, Secret Manager rotation, Artifact Registry cleanup cadence, Docker Scout remediation, Docker MCP uninstall residue, GitHub token/activity hygiene, Actions retention windows, and Atlassian token expiry telemetry.\\n- Batch 007 kept the queue date (`2026-05-10`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-11-signal-radar-batch-008.md` with 8 propagation-lag/stale-state signals across OpenAI retrieval consistency windows, Google IAM propagation, Artifact Registry cleanup cadence, Docker MCP catalog refresh delay, GitHub restore-availability lag, Atlassian token-policy latency, Atlassian pending uninstall behavior, and TeamCity scheduled cleanup.\\n- Batch 008 kept the queue date (`2026-05-11`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-12-signal-radar-batch-009.md` with 8 reversibility/partial-restore signals across Google delayed-destroy and undelete contracts, Docker backup-dependent rollback, GitHub repository/package restore gaps, Atlassian service-project trash recovery, and JetBrains TeamCity artifact-restore limits.\\n- Batch 009 kept the queue date (`2026-05-12`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-13-signal-radar-batch-010.md` with 8 recovery-prerequisite/restore-blocker signals across Google undelete and billing relink gates, GitHub fork-network and namespace blockers, Docker backup-sidecar/path residue requirements, Atlassian admin/email reactivation, and TeamCity empty-target plus encryption-key dependencies.\\n- Batch 010 kept the queue date (`2026-05-13`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-14-signal-radar-batch-011.md` with 8 post-restore verification and rehydration signals across Google billing propagation and restart checks, Google audit/state proof surfaces, GitHub repo/org partial restore gaps, Docker mount-proof surfaces, Atlassian replay gaps, and TeamCity readiness/reindex checks.\\n- Batch 011 kept the queue date (`2026-05-14`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-15-signal-radar-batch-012.md` with 8 post-recovery reconciliation/proof-bundle signals across Google asset diffs and exports, GitHub audit/member export and rebuild-query surfaces, Docker digest plus volume metadata attestations, and Atlassian inbound-email evidence logs.\\n- Batch 012 kept the queue date (`2026-05-15`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-16-signal-radar-batch-013.md` with 8 recovery-drill automation and recurring proof-capture signals across Google backup schedules and compliance reports, GitHub backup loops and remote archives, Docker diagnostics and live logs, Atlassian audit-log webhooks, and TeamCity backup plus readiness surfaces.\\n- Batch 013 kept the queue date (`2026-05-16`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-17-signal-radar-batch-014.md` with 8 recovery-drill blind-spot and excluded-state signals across Google compliance/logging visibility gaps, GitHub Actions external storage plus audit-stream cliffs, Docker volume omissions, Atlassian partial exports and backup allowlists, and TeamCity artifact or queue exclusions.\\n- Batch 014 kept the queue date (`2026-05-17`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-18-signal-radar-batch-015.md` with 8 manual-reattachment and human-checkpoint signals across Google billing and audit-log handoffs, GitHub Actions storage plus runner reseeding, Docker volume and VM-disk sidecars, TeamCity artifact remapping, and Atlassian admin/support restore gates.\\n- Batch 015 kept the queue date (`2026-05-18`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-19-signal-radar-batch-016.md` with 8 identifier-drift and reference-repair signals across Google service-account and region retargeting, Cloud SQL connection-surface rebinding, GitHub Actions storage plus runner-token invalidation, Docker path/container remapping, Atlassian link or group repair, and TeamCity ID-conflict or broken-URL repair.\\n- Batch 016 kept the queue date (`2026-05-19`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-20-signal-radar-batch-017.md` with 8 post-recovery credential-reissuance and auth-rebinding signals across Google KMS or CMEK key re-enable gates, GitHub runner re-registration plus org-permission rebuild, Atlassian app-access or BYOK reapproval steps, and TeamCity secure-value or encryption-key replay paths.\\n- Batch 017 kept the queue date (`2026-05-20`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\n- `python3 -m pytest`\\n  - Result: `collected 0 items`\\n  - Exit code: `5`\\n  - Meaning: this workspace currently has no executable pytest suite in this session; do not treat the repo as test-green.\\n\\n## Inference\\n\\n- Public restore contracts are now clearly time-boxed and uneven: Google uses `30`-day windows for service accounts and projects, GitHub uses `30` days for packages and `90` days for repositories, and Atlassian uses `60` days for Jira service-project trash.\\n- The more important distinction is no longer just \\\"restorable\\\" vs \\\"not restorable\\\"; it is \\\"what preconditions must still hold before restore is even allowed, and what follow-through is required before the restored system is actually live?\\\"\\n- Batch 010 shows that recovery blockers are now explicit product surfaces: name reuse, non-empty fork graphs, admin-role topology, billing relink permissions, same-path disk restore, empty destination databases, and missing encryption keys.\\n- Batch 011 shows the next shift after restore blockers: operators now need proof that reactivation converged, replay debt is understood, sidecars are reattached, and the restored system is actually ready for live use.\\n- Batch 012 shows the next shift after post-restore readiness: recovery trust is now expressed as portable artifacts such as diffable history, exported audit/member state, immutable digests, volume metadata, and raw missed-event payloads.\\n- Batch 013 shows the next shift after proof bundles: the market is starting to expose recurring drill loops directly through schedules, compliance reports, external streams, remote archives, support bundles, and readiness probes.\\n- Batch 014 shows the next shift after recurring drills: vendors are increasingly explicit about what the automation loop does not capture, including omitted payload classes, short proof retention, duplicate or partial streams, and manual-only restore dependencies.\\n- Batch 015 shows the next shift after excluded-state disclosures: the strongest signals are now the explicit human handoff points where billing, audit capture, runner trust, sidecar files, or admin approvals still need to be reattached by hand.\\n- Batch 016 shows the next shift after human checkpoints: even when recovery data is present again, stable names, URLs, tokens, group bindings, and external references often still drift and require a separate repair pass.\\n- Batch 017 shows the next shift after identifier repair: recovered systems often still need fresh trust material or permission replay before they are truly usable, including disabled key versions, invalidated runner tokens, staged app access, BYOK reauthorization, and manually replayed CI secrets.\\n- The emerging editorial story is shifting from reversible delete to recovery-completeness operations: conflict checks, reindex progress, audit-backed rebuild manifests, compliance logs, remote archive sync, mount proofs, ready endpoints, diff exports, and missing-work reports are becoming the real signal surfaces.\\n\\n## Next\\n\\n- Produce batch 018 as a narrow post-recovery session invalidation / stale-trust cleanup pass.\\n- Center batch 018 on:\\n  - sessions that must be refreshed or explicitly invalidated after credential repair or restore,\\n  - cached grants, old tokens, or lingering trust relationships that survive longer than operators expect,\\n  - device, browser, runner, or app re-login and re-enrollment surfaces after trust reset,\\n  - propagation windows between revocation and actual enforcement,\\n  - and official docs that admit recovered access is still incomplete until stale trust is flushed.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n/Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-signal-radar-runner/logs/iteration_020.log:26:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_12\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,240p' /Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-22-signal-radar-batch-019.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# 2026-05-22 Signal Radar Batch 019\\n\\nVerified on 2026-05-05.\\n\\nNote:\\n- The filename follows the queue schedule.\\n- Each signal's `Date` field below refers to the source publication or page-update date when available, not the queue date.\\n\\nFocus:\\n- Post-recovery residual-trust inventory and cleanup attestation\\n- Coverage: user-factor and delegated-app inventories, machine-identity last-use surfaces, active-session and active-token views, runner or agent status inventories, and admin proof pages that let operators compare residual trust against an expected clean baseline\\n\\nMethod:\\n- Facts: only claims directly supported by the linked source page.\\n- Inference: editorial read on why the source matters.\\n- Recommendation: what to watch or how to use the signal in future theme selection.\\n- Confidence: `high`, `medium`, or `low`.\\n\\n## Residual Trust Evidence Captured\\n\\n- Google now exposes residual trust as inspectable metadata instead of a single post-reset verdict: Workspace admins can inspect last-used user factors and delegated apps, while Cloud admins can query last authentication times for service accounts and keys. Sources: https://support.google.com/a/answer/2537800 ; https://docs.cloud.google.com/policy-intelligence/docs/activity-analyzer-service-account-authentication\\n- GitHub splits cleanup attestation across three separate inventories: active sessions by device, active fine-grained PATs by organization, and self-hosted runner status by UI or REST API. Sources: https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/viewing-and-managing-your-sessions ; https://docs.github.com/en/organizations/managing-programmatic-access-to-your-organization/reviewing-and-revoking-personal-access-tokens-in-your-organization ; https://docs.github.com/en/actions/how-tos/manage-runners/self-hosted-runners/monitor-and-troubleshoot ; https://docs.github.com/en/rest/actions/self-hosted-runners\\n- Docker pairs token inventory with corroborating audit evidence: PAT rows expose active state and last-used metadata, while activity logs can attribute actions to PATs or organization access tokens. Sources: https://docs.docker.com/security/access-tokens/ ; https://docs.docker.com/admin/activity-logs/\\n- Atlassian and TeamCity also favor proof tables over a one-click \\\"clean\\\" verdict: recent-device and managed-account exports expose lingering SaaS trust, while TeamCity exposes recently used VCS auth tokens, audit records, and user last-login timestamps. Sources: https://support.atlassian.com/atlassian-account/docs/manage-recently-used-devices-for-your-atlassian-account/ ; https://support.atlassian.com/security-and-access-policies/docs/export-managed-accounts/ ; https://support.atlassian.com/atlassian-cloud/kb/atlassian-administration-what-is-the-difference-between-users-page-and-managed-accounts-page/ ; https://www.jetbrains.com/help/teamcity/manage-access-tokens.html ; https://www.jetbrains.com/help/teamcity/rest/get-audit-records.html ; https://www.jetbrains.com/help/teamcity/rest/user.html\\n\\n## 01. Google Workspace turns post-recovery user trust into a field-by-field security inventory\\n- Date: n/a (docs page, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: admin-visible residual trust metadata for user factors and delegated access\\n- Facts:\\n  - Google says the Passkeys & security keys section displays the name of each enrolled key, the platform or device it was created on, the enrollment method, passwordless support, and when and where the key was added and last used.\\n  - Google says admin log events record each passkey revoke and each security-key revoke.\\n  - Google says the Application-specific password section lists apps using app passwords, and clicking an app shows when the password was created and when it was last used.\\n  - Google says the Connected applications section lists third-party applications with access to the user's account data, including the access level and authorization date.\\n  - Source: https://support.google.com/a/answer/2537800\\n- Inference: Google is treating cleanup attestation as an inspection workflow across enrolled factors, legacy app passwords, and delegated app grants, not as a single \\\"trust cleared\\\" state.\\n- Why it matters: After a recovery or incident reset, operators need to explain every still-live factor and delegated app grant, and Google now exposes most of that residue directly on the user security page.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on how post-recovery proof is shifting from password reset alone to detailed trust-inventory review.\\n- Recommendation: Keep favoring docs that expose last-used factor data, app-password rows, and delegated-app authorization dates in one admin surface; those are strong residual-trust signals.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: Google does not provide a single export or combined report that merges passkeys, app passwords, connected apps, and sign-in-cookie reset status into one cleanup verdict.\\n\\n## 02. Google Cloud treats service-account cleanup as a queryable last-auth surface, with explicit blind spots\\n- Date: n/a (docs page, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: machine-identity residual trust and recent-auth attestation\\n- Facts:\\n  - Google says Activity Analyzer shows when service accounts and service account keys were last used to call a Google API.\\n  - Google says administrators can list the most recent authentication activities for all service accounts or service account keys by using `gcloud policy-intelligence query-activity` or the Policy Analyzer API.\\n  - Google says the console has dedicated panes for \\\"When was the last time this service account was used?\\\" and \\\"When was the last time this service account key was used?\\\" and can analyze up to 10 service accounts or keys at a time.\\n  - Google says results include `lastAuthenticatedTime`, and the key-listing step exposes each key's unique ID, creation time, and expiration time.\\n  - Google says requests authenticated by API keys bound to service accounts are not recorded in service account usage metrics, and activity outside Google Cloud APIs is not tracked by Activity Analyzer or service account insights.\\n  - Source: https://docs.cloud.google.com/policy-intelligence/docs/activity-analyzer-service-account-authentication\\n- Inference: Google is making machine-trust cleanup measurable, but only if operators actively query the right inventory surfaces and cross-check the documented blind spots.\\n- Why it matters: Post-recovery machine cleanup is incomplete without proof that service accounts and keys really stopped authenticating, especially when external or non-Google-Cloud usage can escape the main inventory.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on how cloud recovery increasingly depends on \\\"last authenticated\\\" evidence instead of simple key rotation claims.\\n- Recommendation: Continue prioritizing official docs that publish last-auth query surfaces and their blind spots. They are stronger evidence than generic advice to rotate credentials.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The feature is still labeled Preview and Google does not present a single authoritative view that covers every service-account use case across Cloud and non-Cloud Google APIs.\\n\\n## 03. GitHub's sessions page is an explicit residual-device inventory for both web and mobile access\\n- Date: n/a (docs page, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: active interactive-session inventory and revoke controls\\n- Facts:\\n  - GitHub says users can view a list of devices that have logged into their account and revoke any sessions they do not recognize.\\n  - GitHub says the Sessions settings page shows active web sessions and a list of devices that logged in via the GitHub Mobile app.\\n  - GitHub says users can inspect web-session details and revoke a web session from the details view.\\n  - GitHub says revoking a mobile session signs the user out of the GitHub Mobile application on that device and removes it as a second-factor option.\\n  - Source: https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/viewing-and-managing-your-sessions\\n- Inference: GitHub is exposing cleanup attestation as a human-readable device/session ledger rather than assuming password changes or token rotation already closed the loop.\\n- Why it matters: After recovery, teams often need proof that old browser and mobile trust is actually gone, and GitHub gives end users a direct device inventory for that check.\\n- Article potential: Medium-high for a piece on how consumer-style session lists are becoming part of enterprise recovery evidence.\\n- Recommendation: Track official session-management docs that expose per-device or per-client inventories, not just revoke verbs.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The page documents the user view, but it does not describe an organization-wide admin export or bulk member-session review flow.\\n\\n## 04. GitHub's Active tokens page is a residual-access inventory, but it is intentionally incomplete\\n- Date: n/a (docs page, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: organization-scoped active-token inventory with documented visibility limits\\n- Facts:\\n  - GitHub says organization owners can open Settings > Personal access tokens > Active tokens to display any fine-grained personal access tokens that can access the organization.\\n  - GitHub says owners can filter the displayed tokens by owner, repository access, and permission set before revoking them.\\n  - GitHub says organization owners can also use REST API endpoints to review and revoke fine-grained personal access tokens, but only via GitHub Apps and not via personal access tokens or OAuth apps.\\n  - GitHub says organization owners cannot view or revoke personal access tokens (classic) in this UI, and unless classic PAT access has been restricted, any classic PAT can access organization resources until it expires.\\n  - Source: https://docs.github.com/en/organizations/managing-programmatic-access-to-your-organization/reviewing-and-revoking-personal-access-tokens-in-your-organization\\n- Inference: GitHub is giving admins a meaningful residual-token inventory, but also drawing a sharp line around which credential classes that inventory can and cannot prove clean.\\n- Why it matters: Cleanup attestation can be misleading if operators treat the Active tokens page as a complete token ledger when GitHub explicitly documents classic-PAT blind spots.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on why token cleanup proof is only as good as the visibility model behind the inventory page.\\n- Recommendation: Keep highlighting docs that document both the visible token inventory and the classes of credentials that remain outside it.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The docs describe filterable visibility but do not publish a built-in last-used field for the Active tokens inventory.\\n\\n## 05. GitHub self-hosted runner status has become a machine-trust inventory, not just a troubleshooting aid\\n- Date: n/a (docs pages, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: runner fleet inventory and post-recovery re-enrollment proof\\n- Facts:\\n  - GitHub says the Actions > Runners page lists registered self-hosted runners with the runner name, labels, and status.\\n  - GitHub says runner status can be `Idle`, `Active`, or `Offline`.\\n  - GitHub's REST API for self-hosted runners returns structured runner records that include `id`, `name`, `os`, `status`, `busy`, `ephemeral`, and `labels`.\\n  - GitHub says administrators can use REST endpoints to list runners for an organization or repository.\\n  - Sources: https://docs.github.com/en/actions/how-tos/manage-runners/self-hosted-runners/monitor-and-troubleshoot ; https://docs.github.com/en/rest/actions/self-hosted-runners\\n- Inference: The runner-control plane is effectively a residual machine-trust inventory now; after recovery, operators can compare which runner identities remain online, offline, or unexpectedly present.\\n- Why it matters: Runner cleanup and re-enrollment are central post-recovery tasks, and GitHub now exposes enough status metadata to distinguish \\\"registered but dead,\\\" \\\"alive and busy,\\\" and \\\"should no longer exist.\\\"\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on how CI recovery increasingly depends on agent inventory surfaces rather than one-time re-registration steps.\\n- Recommendation: Keep prioritizing vendor docs that expose both UI and API runner inventories with explicit status fields.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: GitHub does not provide a native baseline-diff report that says which runners are unexpected after a reset; operators must compare the current list against their own clean-state expectation.\\n\\n## 06. Docker ties residual CLI trust to two separate proof surfaces: token rows and attributable activity logs\\n- Date: n/a (docs pages, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: token last-used inventory plus audit corroboration\\n- Facts:\\n  - Docker says the Personal access tokens page shows an overview of all tokens, including whether each token was manually generated or auto-generated, its scope, whether it is active or inactive, when it was created, when it was last used, and its expiration date.\\n  - Docker says users can rename, activate, deactivate, or delete a token from that page.\\n  - Docker says organization activity logs let owners view what changes were made, when a change was made, and who initiated it.\\n  - Docker says activity-log event descriptions that include a user action can refer to a Docker username, a personal access token, or an organization access token.\\n  - Docker says the Activity tab shows events from the last 30 days by default, and longer retrieval requires the Docker Hub API.\\n  - Sources: https://docs.docker.com/security/access-tokens/ ; https://docs.docker.com/admin/activity-logs/\\n- Inference: Docker is making token cleanup attestable through a join of token metadata and audit attribution, not through a single \\\"all CLI trust removed\\\" statement.\\n- Why it matters: Post-recovery Docker cleanup needs both an inventory of still-live tokens and a corroborating activity trail that can reveal whether a token or OAT is still being used.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on how developer platforms are exposing token residue through last-used fields and audit attribution instead of only rotation guidance.\\n- Recommendation: Favor docs that expose both token last-used metadata and audit events that identify token-originated actions.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: Docker does not document a single built-in report that joins token inventory, token last-used metadata, and all historical PAT/OAT actions beyond the UI retention window.\\n\\n## 07. Atlassian splits cleanup attestation across recent-device views, managed-account exports, and per-user token metadata\\n- Date: n/a (docs pages and support KB, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: SaaS account residual-trust inventory across interactive and non-interactive surfaces\\n- Facts:\\n  - Atlassian says the recent devices list shows devices that are currently logged in to the account, including browser or mobile-app context, IP address, and either last login or last mobile-app use time.\\n  - Atlassian says non-interactive logins, such as calls that use API tokens, do not appear in the recent devices list.\\n  - Atlassian says organization admins can export managed accounts to CSV, including each account's last active time, status, policy name and type, SAML SSO status, two-step-verification status, password requirements, idle session duration, and product/site access.\\n  - Atlassian's support KB says the managed-account detail page lets org admins view and control API tokens, including `Last accessed` and `Created on`, and also administer recently used devices.\\n  - Sources: https://support.atlassian.com/atlassian-account/docs/manage-recently-used-devices-for-your-atlassian-account/ ; https://support.atlassian.com/security-and-access-policies/docs/export-managed-accounts/ ; https://support.atlassian.com/atlassian-cloud/kb/atlassian-administration-what-is-the-difference-between-users-page-and-managed-accounts-page/\\n- Inference: Atlassian is exposing post-recovery proof as a set of adjacent inventories: interactive device residue, account-level activity and policy state, and per-user API token metadata.\\n- Why it matters: Recovery cleanup can look complete if teams inspect only recent devices, while API-token or account-policy residue remains visible elsewhere.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on how SaaS admins increasingly need multi-surface account inventories to prove trust cleanup.\\n- Recommendation: Keep preferring vendor docs that explicitly say which trust classes are visible in each inventory and which are excluded.\\n- Confidence: medium-high\\n- Evidence gaps: Atlassian does not document a single export that combines recent devices, API-token last-accessed data, and managed-account policy state into one cleanup-attestation artifact.\\n\\n## 08. TeamCity exposes residual trust through \\\"recently used\\\" tokens, last-login fields, and filterable audit records\\n- Date: n/a (docs pages, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: CI admin proof surfaces for token reuse and user activity\\n- Facts:\\n  - JetBrains says the VCS Auth Tokens page provides centralized access to refreshable tokens for a project and its subprojects, lets admins find tokens by name, related connection, and issuing user, and without filters shows the 10 most recently used tokens.\\n  - JetBrains says the TeamCity user REST resource includes a `lastLogin` property that records the date and time when a user last logged in.\\n  - JetBrains says audit records are available on the Administration | Audit page and via `/app/rest/audit`.\\n  - JetBrains says the audit REST API supports filters such as `count`, `user`, and `action`.\\n  - Sources: https://www.jetbrains.com/help/teamcity/manage-access-tokens.html ; https://www.jetbrains.com/help/teamcity/rest/user.html ; https://www.jetbrains.com/help/teamcity/rest/get-audit-records.html ; https://www.jetbrains.com/help/teamcity/tracking-user-actions.html\\n- Inference: TeamCity is treating cleanup attestation as an admin toolkit of separate inventories and logs rather than a single session or token dashboard.\\n- Why it matters: After recovery, CI operators need to answer which VCS auth tokens were recently active, which users still logged in, and what sensitive actions were taken, and TeamCity now exposes each of those questions through different proof surfaces.\\n- Article potential: Medium-high for a piece on how CI systems are surfacing residual trust through admin artifacts instead of a one-shot \\\"secure again\\\" marker.\\n- Recommendation: Watch for vendor docs that combine \\\"recently used,\\\" `lastLogin`, and audit filtering. Those are strong clues that post-recovery proof is becoming an operator-led reconciliation workflow.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: JetBrains does not document a single server-wide view that merges all access tokens, active sessions, and recent logins into one cleanup verdict.\\n\\n## Current Editorial Read\\n\\n- Facts:\\n  - The strongest official signals in this batch are inventory-first: Google shows last-used factors and service-account auth times, GitHub shows active sessions, active fine-grained PATs, and runner status, Docker shows token last-used state and token-attributed activity logs, Atlassian shows recent devices plus last-active account exports, and TeamCity shows recently used VCS auth tokens plus last-login and audit records.\\n  - These proof surfaces are intentionally partial. Google documents service-account activity blind spots, GitHub documents classic-PAT visibility gaps, Docker limits the UI activity window to 30 days, Atlassian excludes API-token logins from recent devices, and TeamCity spreads the evidence across multiple pages and APIs.\\n  - The recovery sequence has evolved again: restore -> reissue trust -> flush stale trust -> inventory residual trust -> explain every remaining device, token, runner, key, or app grant.\\n- Inference:\\n  - The next strong editorial move after stale-trust cleanup is baseline comparison. Vendors now expose enough inventory surface to ask why a specific residual item is still present, but they rarely provide the answer automatically.\\n  - Post-recovery proof is becoming a cross-table reconciliation exercise, not a single revoke or restore event.\\n- Recommendation:\\n  - Queue the next batch around post-recovery baseline diff and cleanup exception queues: pending approvals, offline runners or devices that should be gone, unmanaged tokens outside policy, and unresolved residual-trust mismatches that remain after the inventory pass.\\n  - Keep preferring official docs that expose filterable exception lists, last-used metadata, or policy-mismatch exports over docs that only describe how to revoke access.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n/Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-signal-radar-runner/logs/iteration_020.log:62:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_31\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,130p' /Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-signal-radar-runner/memory/CONTEXT.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Theme Signal Radar Context\\n\\n## Fact\\n\\n- Shared workspace:\\n  - `workspace/theme-exploration-shared` points to `/Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-exploration-shared`.\\n  - Write output only to `signals/`.\\n- Signal standard:\\n  - Separate facts, inferences, and recommendations.\\n  - Preserve source URLs for every factual claim.\\n  - Prefer primary or near-primary sources.\\n  - Mark confidence as high, medium, or low.\\n  - Do not invent missing facts; weak sourcing requires an evidence-gap note.\\n- 2026-05-04: created `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-04-signal-radar-batch-001.md` with 31 source-backed signals across AI agents, coding agents, AI devtools, AI infra/pricing, creative AI, local-first tools, open-source productization, and content automation.\\n- 2026-05-04: created `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-05-signal-radar-batch-002.md` with 12 protocol/distribution signals on MCP, A2A, ACP, managed endpoints, registry surfaces, and IDE support.\\n- 2026-05-04: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-06-signal-radar-batch-003.md` with 10 control-plane signals across approvals, auth, quotas, sandboxing, registry trust, and tool-surface minimization.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-07-signal-radar-batch-004.md` with 9 observability/accountability signals across traces, eval loops, compliance logs, usage metering, session logs, and post-action review.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-08-signal-radar-batch-005.md` with 9 change-control/provenance signals across frozen snapshots, action diffs, model pinning, immutable revisions, signed attestations, verified catalogs, and plugin signing/review.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-09-signal-radar-batch-006.md` with 8 revocation/rollback signals across model retirement, attestation deletion, undeploy semantics, uninstall residue, plugin hide/remove flows, token revoke, and app-surface disable paths.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-10-signal-radar-batch-007.md` with 9 expiry/hygiene signals across Realtime token TTLs, vector-store expiry and cleanup lag, Secret Manager rotation, Artifact Registry cleanup cadence, Docker Scout remediation, Docker MCP uninstall residue, GitHub token/activity hygiene, Actions retention windows, and Atlassian token expiry telemetry.\\n- Batch 007 kept the queue date (`2026-05-10`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-11-signal-radar-batch-008.md` with 8 propagation-lag/stale-state signals across OpenAI retrieval consistency windows, Google IAM propagation, Artifact Registry cleanup cadence, Docker MCP catalog refresh delay, GitHub restore-availability lag, Atlassian token-policy latency, Atlassian pending uninstall behavior, and TeamCity scheduled cleanup.\\n- Batch 008 kept the queue date (`2026-05-11`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-12-signal-radar-batch-009.md` with 8 reversibility/partial-restore signals across Google delayed-destroy and undelete contracts, Docker backup-dependent rollback, GitHub repository/package restore gaps, Atlassian service-project trash recovery, and JetBrains TeamCity artifact-restore limits.\\n- Batch 009 kept the queue date (`2026-05-12`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-13-signal-radar-batch-010.md` with 8 recovery-prerequisite/restore-blocker signals across Google undelete and billing relink gates, GitHub fork-network and namespace blockers, Docker backup-sidecar/path residue requirements, Atlassian admin/email reactivation, and TeamCity empty-target plus encryption-key dependencies.\\n- Batch 010 kept the queue date (`2026-05-13`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-14-signal-radar-batch-011.md` with 8 post-restore verification and rehydration signals across Google billing propagation and restart checks, Google audit/state proof surfaces, GitHub repo/org partial restore gaps, Docker mount-proof surfaces, Atlassian replay gaps, and TeamCity readiness/reindex checks.\\n- Batch 011 kept the queue date (`2026-05-14`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-15-signal-radar-batch-012.md` with 8 post-recovery reconciliation/proof-bundle signals across Google asset diffs and exports, GitHub audit/member export and rebuild-query surfaces, Docker digest plus volume metadata attestations, and Atlassian inbound-email evidence logs.\\n- Batch 012 kept the queue date (`2026-05-15`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-16-signal-radar-batch-013.md` with 8 recovery-drill automation and recurring proof-capture signals across Google backup schedules and compliance reports, GitHub backup loops and remote archives, Docker diagnostics and live logs, Atlassian audit-log webhooks, and TeamCity backup plus readiness surfaces.\\n- Batch 013 kept the queue date (`2026-05-16`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-17-signal-radar-batch-014.md` with 8 recovery-drill blind-spot and excluded-state signals across Google compliance/logging visibility gaps, GitHub Actions external storage plus audit-stream cliffs, Docker volume omissions, Atlassian partial exports and backup allowlists, and TeamCity artifact or queue exclusions.\\n- Batch 014 kept the queue date (`2026-05-17`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-18-signal-radar-batch-015.md` with 8 manual-reattachment and human-checkpoint signals across Google billing and audit-log handoffs, GitHub Actions storage plus runner reseeding, Docker volume and VM-disk sidecars, TeamCity artifact remapping, and Atlassian admin/support restore gates.\\n- Batch 015 kept the queue date (`2026-05-18`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-19-signal-radar-batch-016.md` with 8 identifier-drift and reference-repair signals across Google service-account and region retargeting, Cloud SQL connection-surface rebinding, GitHub Actions storage plus runner-token invalidation, Docker path/container remapping, Atlassian link or group repair, and TeamCity ID-conflict or broken-URL repair.\\n- Batch 016 kept the queue date (`2026-05-19`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-20-signal-radar-batch-017.md` with 8 post-recovery credential-reissuance and auth-rebinding signals across Google KMS or CMEK key re-enable gates, GitHub runner re-registration plus org-permission rebuild, Atlassian app-access or BYOK reapproval steps, and TeamCity secure-value or encryption-key replay paths.\\n- Batch 017 kept the queue date (`2026-05-20`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-21-signal-radar-batch-018.md` with 8 post-recovery session-invalidation and stale-trust-cleanup signals across Google sign-in-cookie plus IdP-session residue and IAM propagation, GitHub SSO or PAT residue, Docker CLI PAT continuity under SSO enforcement, Atlassian logout timing, and TeamCity server-wide trust purge controls.\\n- Batch 018 kept the queue date (`2026-05-21`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-22-signal-radar-batch-019.md` with 8 post-recovery residual-trust-inventory and cleanup-attestation signals across Google user-security and service-account last-use surfaces, GitHub sessions plus active-token and runner inventories, Docker PAT last-used and audit-log proof, Atlassian recent-device and managed-account exports, and TeamCity recently used auth-token plus audit/login metadata.\\n- Batch 019 kept the queue date (`2026-05-22`) separate from the verification date (`2026-05-05`).\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\n- `python3 -m pytest`\\n  - Result: `collected 0 items`\\n  - Exit code: `5`\\n  - Meaning: this workspace currently has no executable pytest suite in this session; do not treat the repo as test-green.\\n\\n## Inference\\n\\n- Public restore contracts are now clearly time-boxed and uneven: Google uses `30`-day windows for service accounts and projects, GitHub uses `30` days for packages and `90` days for repositories, and Atlassian uses `60` days for Jira service-project trash.\\n- The more important distinction is no longer just \\\"restorable\\\" vs \\\"not restorable\\\"; it is \\\"what preconditions must still hold before restore is even allowed, and what follow-through is required before the restored system is actually live?\\\"\\n- Batch 010 shows that recovery blockers are now explicit product surfaces: name reuse, non-empty fork graphs, admin-role topology, billing relink permissions, same-path disk restore, empty destination databases, and missing encryption keys.\\n- Batch 011 shows the next shift after restore blockers: operators now need proof that reactivation converged, replay debt is understood, sidecars are reattached, and the restored system is actually ready for live use.\\n- Batch 012 shows the next shift after post-restore readiness: recovery trust is now expressed as portable artifacts such as diffable history, exported audit/member state, immutable digests, volume metadata, and raw missed-event payloads.\\n- Batch 013 shows the next shift after proof bundles: the market is starting to expose recurring drill loops directly through schedules, compliance reports, external streams, remote archives, support bundles, and readiness probes.\\n- Batch 014 shows the next shift after recurring drills: vendors are increasingly explicit about what the automation loop does not capture, including omitted payload classes, short proof retention, duplicate or partial streams, and manual-only restore dependencies.\\n- Batch 015 shows the next shift after excluded-state disclosures: the strongest signals are now the explicit human handoff points where billing, audit capture, runner trust, sidecar files, or admin approvals still need to be reattached by hand.\\n- Batch 016 shows the next shift after human checkpoints: even when recovery data is present again, stable names, URLs, tokens, group bindings, and external references often still drift and require a separate repair pass.\\n- Batch 017 shows the next shift after identifier repair: recovered systems often still need fresh trust material or permission replay before they are truly usable, including disabled key versions, invalidated runner tokens, staged app access, BYOK reauthorization, and manually replayed CI secrets.\\n- Batch 018 shows the next shift after credential repair: issuing fresh trust is still insufficient until old cookies, old SSO sessions, old PATs, and delayed revocation windows are explicitly flushed and allowed to converge.\\n- Batch 019 shows the next shift after stale-trust cleanup: vendors increasingly expose fragmented inspection surfaces for what trust is still alive, such as last-used factors, recent devices, active PAT inventories, runner status tables, service-account auth times, and recently used CI auth tokens, but rarely provide a single \\\"clean baseline reached\\\" verdict.\\n- The emerging editorial story is shifting from reversible delete to recovery-completeness operations: conflict checks, reindex progress, audit-backed rebuild manifests, compliance logs, remote archive sync, mount proofs, ready endpoints, diff exports, residual-trust inventories, and cleanup exception queues are becoming the real signal surfaces.\\n\\n## Next\\n\\n- Produce batch 020 as a narrow post-recovery baseline-diff / cleanup-exception-queue pass.\\n- Center batch 020 on:\\n  - official surfaces that show which tokens, devices, runners, accounts, or approvals are still pending, offline, unmanaged, or otherwise out of baseline after the inventory pass,\\n  - filterable exports or dashboards that highlight policy mismatches instead of just listing all current access,\\n  - vendor docs that turn lingering residual-trust items into explicit exception queues,\\n  - and proof surfaces that help operators distinguish \\\"expected active\\\" from \\\"unexpected still active\\\" after recovery.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n/Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-signal-radar-runner/logs/iteration_008.log:13:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_5\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-10-signal-radar-batch-007.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# 2026-05-10 Signal Radar Batch 007\\n\\nVerified on 2026-05-05.\\n\\nNote:\\n- The filename follows the queue schedule.\\n- Each signal's `Date` field below refers to the source publication date when available, not the queue date.\\n\\nFocus:\\n- Protocol expiry and hygiene automation\\n- Coverage: token TTLs, expiring storage, secret rotation, artifact cleanup, stale-image remediation, uninstall residue, retention windows, and dormant-access cleanup\\n\\nMethod:\\n- Facts: only claims directly supported by the linked source page.\\n- Inference: editorial read on why the source matters.\\n- Recommendation: what to watch or how to use the signal in future theme selection.\\n- Confidence: `high`, `medium`, or `low`.\\n\\n## Expiry And Hygiene Evidence Captured\\n\\n- OpenAI now exposes explicit short-lived and expiring objects: Realtime client secrets expire after one minute, vector stores can expire off `last_active_at`, and removed vector-store files can linger briefly because deletion is eventually consistent. Sources: https://developers.openai.com/api/reference/resources/realtime/subresources/client_secrets ; https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/retrieval\\n- Google provides first-party rotation and cleanup schedulers: Secret Manager emits `SECRET_ROTATE` messages on a schedule, while Artifact Registry applies delete/keep cleanup policies via a periodic background job. Sources: https://docs.cloud.google.com/secret-manager/docs/secret-rotation ; https://docs.cloud.google.com/artifact-registry/docs/repositories/cleanup-policy-overview\\n- Docker splits hygiene into two layers: Scout can generate guided or GitHub-backed remediation for stale base images, but MCP server removal still leaves images and credentials behind until operators clean them manually. Sources: https://docs.docker.com/scout/policy/remediation/ ; https://docs.docker.com/ai/mcp-catalog-and-toolkit/faqs/ ; https://docs.docker.com/ai/mcp-catalog-and-toolkit/profiles/ ; https://docs.docker.com/security/access-tokens/\\n- GitHub applies hygiene to both auth and build residue: tokens auto-revoke on expiry, inactivity, or public leaks, orgs can block overlong PAT lifetimes, and Actions artifacts/logs auto-delete after retention windows. Sources: https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/token-expiration-and-revocation ; https://docs.github.com/en/organizations/managing-programmatic-access-to-your-organization/setting-a-personal-access-token-policy-for-your-organization ; https://docs.github.com/en/organizations/managing-organization-settings/configuring-the-retention-period-for-github-actions-artifacts-and-logs-in-your-organization?apiVersion=2022-11-28\\n- Atlassian is turning token hygiene into both default policy and centralized telemetry: API tokens default to one-year expiry, can be tightened by authentication policy, and admins can inspect creation/expiry/last-used state from one place. Sources: https://support.atlassian.com/atlassian-account/docs/manage-api-tokens-for-your-atlassian-account/ ; https://support.atlassian.com/organization-administration/docs/understand-user-api-tokens/ ; https://support.atlassian.com/security-and-access-policies/docs/authentication-policy-settings-for-your-organizations/\\n\\n## 01. OpenAI's browser-safe Realtime auth is hard-capped at one minute\\n- Date: n/a (docs page, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: short-lived token TTLs\\n- Facts:\\n  - OpenAI's Realtime client secret reference says the `client_secret` object includes `expires_at`.\\n  - The same page says \\\"Currently, all tokens expire after one minute.\\\"\\n  - The session response object also exposes an `expires_at` field for the client secret.\\n  - Source: https://developers.openai.com/api/reference/resources/realtime/subresources/client_secrets\\n- Inference: OpenAI is treating browser-facing agent auth as intentionally disposable, not as a long-lived credential that should survive outside a narrow connection setup window.\\n- Why it matters: Short TTLs are becoming a concrete platform primitive for agent safety, especially where client-side or browser-side tool access is involved.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on how agent platforms are normalizing \\\"ephemeral by default\\\" for risky execution surfaces.\\n- Recommendation: Track whether other agent vendors start publishing similarly short default TTLs for browser-safe or delegated auth flows.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The public reference does not describe configurable TTL ranges, grace periods, or refresh-token style renewal behavior for these client secrets.\\n\\n## 02. OpenAI is productizing storage expiry, but cleanup visibility still has lag\\n- Date: n/a (docs page, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: expiring knowledge stores and cleanup lag\\n- Facts:\\n  - OpenAI's retrieval guide says you can set an expiration policy on `vector_store` objects with `expires_after`.\\n  - The same guide says that once a vector store expires, all associated `vector_store.file` objects are deleted and you are no longer charged for them.\\n  - OpenAI's example uses `anchor: \\\"last_active_at\\\"` with `days: 7`.\\n  - The guide also says removing files from a vector store is eventually consistent, and search results may still include content from a removed file for a short period.\\n  - Source: https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/retrieval\\n- Inference: OpenAI has moved beyond simple deletion endpoints into lifecycle-aware storage hygiene, but it is still transparent that cleanup is not instantaneous at query time.\\n- Why it matters: This is exactly the kind of operational detail that determines whether \\\"expired\\\" or \\\"removed\\\" really means gone for an agent stack that keeps searching old context.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on why expiry policy and consistency windows matter as much as raw delete verbs.\\n- Recommendation: Track whether OpenAI adds pre-expiry alerts, stronger deletion SLAs, or admin surfaces that show pending cleanup state.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The public guide does not describe alerting before expiry, a default expiry for all vector stores, or precise consistency timing for removed files.\\n\\n## 03. Google Secret Manager turns secret rotation into a scheduled message bus\\n- Date: n/a (docs page, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: secret rotation automation\\n- Facts:\\n  - Google's Secret Manager rotation docs say Secret Manager triggers a `SECRET_ROTATE` message to designated Pub/Sub topics at the secret's `next_rotation_time`.\\n  - The docs say `next_rotation_time` can be set directly or calculated automatically from `rotation_period`.\\n  - After the specified `rotation_period` elapses, Secret Manager sends the notification and updates `next_rotation_time` to schedule the next rotation.\\n  - Google says customers must configure a Pub/Sub subscriber to receive and act on these messages.\\n  - Source: https://docs.cloud.google.com/secret-manager/docs/secret-rotation\\n- Inference: Google is exposing rotation scheduling as first-party infrastructure, while leaving the actual credential replacement workflow pluggable.\\n- Why it matters: This is a useful benchmark for agent platforms that talk about secret hygiene but still make operators bolt together reminders or cron jobs themselves.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on which platforms provide native rotation clocks versus just telling teams to rotate manually.\\n- Recommendation: Track whether agent registries and tool platforms add equivalent scheduled rotation hooks for OAuth grants, API keys, or MCP secrets.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The docs do not promise automatic secret replacement, rollback, or drift detection if the subscriber fails to rotate the secret after the notification arrives.\\n\\n## 04. Google Artifact Registry makes stale-version cleanup policy-driven, but not immediate\\n- Date: last updated 2026-01-02 UTC\\n- Theme family: artifact garbage collection and retention policy\\n- Facts:\\n  - Google's Artifact Registry cleanup-policy docs say you can define delete policies for artifact age or other criteria, plus keep policies to retain artifacts you still want.\\n  - If an artifact matches both a delete and keep policy, the keep policy wins.\\n  - The docs show cleanup jobs running as a periodic background task, and say changes take effect within approximately one day.\\n  - Delete-policy executions count against quota and are limited to `300,000` deletions per repository per day.\\n  - Source: https://docs.cloud.google.com/artifact-registry/docs/repositories/cleanup-policy-overview\\n- Inference: Google treats cleanup as a managed background control plane, but it is explicit that garbage collection is batchy rather than real-time.\\n- Why it matters: Expiry and cleanup claims are materially different when the operator-visible enforcement window is \\\"within approximately one day.\\\"\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on the hidden timing contract of cleanup automation across modern agent and artifact systems.\\n- Recommendation: Track whether Artifact Registry or analogous agent catalogs add dry-run previews, alerts before deletion, or faster cadence options for high-risk repos.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The public docs do not describe real-time stale-artifact alerts, per-policy execution histories, or stronger guarantees for when deletions become visible to downstream consumers.\\n\\n## 05. Docker Scout is turning stale-base-image hygiene into guided and automated remediation\\n- Date: n/a (docs page, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: stale-image remediation\\n- Facts:\\n  - Docker's Scout remediation docs say the Up-to-Date Base Images policy checks whether the base image you use is up-to-date.\\n  - When provenance attestations are present, Docker Scout cross-references the detected base image version against the current version of the tag.\\n  - If there is a policy violation, Docker says the recommended actions show how to update the base image to the latest version while pinning it to a specific digest.\\n  - With GitHub integration enabled, Docker says users can raise a pull request from the remediation side panel and that the PR automatically updates the Dockerfile to the up-to-date base image version.\\n  - Source: https://docs.docker.com/scout/policy/remediation/\\n- Inference: Docker is moving from passive warning surfaces to active hygiene workflows that can directly propose supply-chain refreshes.\\n- Why it matters: \\\"Stale base image\\\" is increasingly a first-class drift signal, and Docker is treating remediation as a product surface rather than a separate security chore.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on how image freshness is becoming operationalized like dependency updates or secret rotation.\\n- Recommendation: Track whether other agent-tool registries add equivalent fix proposals for stale servers, outdated manifests, or missing attestations.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The docs do not describe alerting cadence, merge automation, or org-level policies that require remediation before deployment.\\n\\n## 06. Docker's hygiene story is mixed: some token cleanup is automatic, MCP residue cleanup is not\\n- Date: n/a (docs pages, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: token lifecycle hygiene and uninstall residue\\n- Facts:\\n  - Docker's personal access token docs say PAT creation includes an expiration date, and that you cannot edit the expiration date on an existing PAT.\\n  - The same docs say the token overview shows whether tokens are active or inactive, when they were created, when they were last used, and their expiration date.\\n  - Docker also documents auto-generated Docker Desktop tokens as session-based, automatically removed when the Desktop session expires, with older auto-generated tokens deleted when new ones are created.\\n  - Docker's MCP Toolkit FAQ says credentials for MCP servers can be managed with `docker mcp secret rm` and `docker mcp oauth revoke`.\\n  - The same FAQ says removing an MCP server stops the container but leaves the image on the system, and credentials remain stored until users remove them manually.\\n  - Docker also says a local MCP catalog can go stale and may need `docker mcp catalog update` before remote servers appear.\\n  - Docker's profiles docs say OAuth credentials are shared across all profiles, so switching accounts requires revoking and re-authorizing.\\n  - Sources: https://docs.docker.com/security/access-tokens/ ; https://docs.docker.com/ai/mcp-catalog-and-toolkit/faqs/ ; https://docs.docker.com/ai/mcp-catalog-and-toolkit/profiles/\\n- Inference: Docker has meaningful automatic hygiene for some auth surfaces, but installed-tool residue and cross-profile OAuth scope are still operator-managed cleanup problems.\\n- Why it matters: This is a concrete example of the market split between expiring credentials cleanly and actually cleaning the rest of the local execution footprint.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on why uninstall residue and shared-credential scope are the missing half of agent-tool governance.\\n- Recommendation: Track whether Docker adds one-shot uninstall cleanup, residue scanners, profile-scoped OAuth, or stale-catalog alerts instead of manual refresh commands.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The public docs do not describe automatic residue detection, credential GC after profile removal, or policy hooks that prevent stale shared OAuth grants from leaking across profiles.\\n\\n## 07. GitHub turns token hygiene into auto-revocation plus org-level lifetime policy\\n- Date: n/a (docs pages, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: dormant-access cleanup and token lifetime governance\\n- Facts:\\n  - GitHub's token-expiration docs say a personal access token is automatically revoked when it reaches its expiration date.\\n  - The same docs say GitHub automatically revokes an OAuth token or personal access token when it has not been used in one year.\\n  - GitHub also says a valid OAuth token, GitHub App token, or personal access token pushed to a public repository or public gist is automatically revoked.\\n  - When a token expires or is revoked, GitHub says the security log may show an `oauth_authorization.destroy` action.\\n  - GitHub's org PAT policy docs say owners can set maximum lifetime allowances for fine-grained PATs and classic PATs.\\n  - The same page says the default maximum lifetime policy for fine-grained PATs in organizations is `366` days, and tokens with non-compliant lifetimes are blocked from accessing the organization.\\n  - Sources: https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/token-expiration-and-revocation ; https://docs.github.com/en/organizations/managing-programmatic-access-to-your-organization/setting-a-personal-access-token-policy-for-your-organization\\n- Inference: GitHub is converging on a layered hygiene stack: token owners choose expirations, inactivity is cleaned up automatically, public leaks are revoked, and orgs can impose stronger lifetime bounds than the user chose.\\n- Why it matters: Dormant or overlong credentials are one of the cleanest measurable hygiene problems in agent tooling, and GitHub now exposes multiple enforcement layers around them.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on how code platforms are making dormant-access cleanup part of the normal auth contract.\\n- Recommendation: Track whether more agent vendors add inactivity-based revocation, security-log hooks, and org-enforced TTL ceilings for delegated tool access.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: GitHub's org policy blocks non-compliant tokens from org access but does not globally revoke them, so stale credentials can still exist outside the org boundary.\\n\\n## 08. GitHub makes CI build residue auto-expire by default\\n- Date: n/a (docs page, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: artifact retention windows\\n- Facts:\\n  - GitHub's Actions retention docs say artifacts and log files are retained for `90` days by default before they are automatically deleted.\\n  - Public-repo retention can be set between `1` and `90` days.\\n  - Private-repo retention can be set between `1` and `400` days.\\n  - GitHub says retention changes apply only to new artifacts and logs, not retroactively to existing ones.\\n  - Source: https://docs.github.com/en/organizations/managing-organization-settings/configuring-the-retention-period-for-github-actions-artifacts-and-logs-in-your-organization?apiVersion=2022-11-28\\n- Inference: GitHub treats build residue cleanup as default-on storage hygiene rather than an optional janitor task.\\n- Why it matters: Agent and workflow platforms increasingly leave behind logs, traces, eval artifacts, and temporary outputs; GitHub is one of the clearest examples of making those byproducts auto-expire on a centralized policy.\\n- Article potential: Medium-high for a piece on how platforms differ between \\\"store forever unless deleted\\\" and \\\"retention is a core admin control.\\\"\\n- Recommendation: Track whether other agent runtimes add equally simple org-level retention controls for traces, transcripts, and tool outputs.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The docs do not describe retroactive shrink operations, tiered retention by workflow class, or alerting when teams are approaching the retention cap they configured.\\n\\n## 09. Atlassian is turning API token hygiene into both default policy and centralized telemetry\\n- Date: n/a (docs pages, verified 2026-05-05)\\n- Theme family: token expiry defaults and admin-side visibility\\n- Facts:\\n  - Atlassian's API token docs say new API tokens expire in one year by default, and users can set expiration from `1` to `365` days when creating a token.\\n  - The same docs say scoped API tokens can be created for Jira or Confluence and cannot be recovered later once the value is dismissed.\\n  - Atlassian's admin docs say organization admins can monitor API token activity from one central location, including how many active tokens exist, when they were created, when they expire, and the last time they were used.\\n  - The admin docs also say admins can revoke one or more tokens from that centralized location.\\n  - Atlassian's authentication-policy docs say orgs can allow or block members from creating new or using existing API tokens, and can set policy-level token expiry between `1` and `365` days.\\n  - The same page says it can take up to `10` minutes for allow/block updates to complete.\\n  - Sources: https://support.atlassian.com/atlassian-account/docs/manage-api-tokens-for-your-atlassian-account/ ; https://support.atlassian.com/organization-administration/docs/understand-user-api-tokens/ ; https://support.atlassian.com/security-and-access-policies/docs/authentication-policy-settings-for-your-organizations/\\n- Inference: Atlassian is treating token hygiene as a full admin surface: default expiry, centralized token inventory, policy-based blocking, and observable update timing.\\n- Why it matters: This is closer to what enterprise agent governance probably needs: not just token creation and revocation, but centralized visibility into dormant or overprivileged machine access.\\n- Article potential: High for a piece on why admin telemetry and propagation timing are becoming part of the auth contract, not just backend implementation details.\\n- Recommendation: Track whether Atlassian adds automatic last-used-based revocation, dormant-token alerts, or cleanup reporting for app-side data after a token is blocked.\\n- Confidence: high\\n- Evidence gaps: The public docs do not describe automatic inactivity revocation, per-token alerting thresholds, or whether blocked tokens trigger downstream cleanup of artifacts or cached app sessions.\\n\\n## Current Editorial Read\\n\\n- Facts:\\n  - Public hygiene controls now span seconds, minutes, hours, days, and manual cleanup: OpenAI Realtime uses a one-minute token TTL, Atlassian documents up to a 10-minute token-policy propagation window, Artifact Registry cleanup can take about a day, and Docker MCP uninstall residue can persist until an operator intervenes.\\n  - Several vendors now auto-expire credentials or build residue, but fewer auto-clean the residual images, credentials, or cached search state left behind after a server or artifact is \\\"removed.\\\"\\n  - Drift remediation is becoming a product surface of its own: Docker Scout already offers guided and GitHub-backed refresh flows for stale base images.\\n- Inference:\\n  - Hygiene automation is emerging as a layer below revocation: the real question is not only whether access can be invalidated, but how long stale state survives afterward.\\n  - The most interesting competitive gap is now timing: TTL length, garbage-collection cadence, eventual consistency windows, and policy propagation delay are all becoming observable platform contracts.\\n- Recommendation:\\n  - Prioritize article themes that compare \\\"expired,\\\" \\\"removed,\\\" and \\\"actually gone\\\" across agent platforms, because the timing gap is where operational risk still hides.\\n  - Next batch should focus on propagation lag and stale-state windows: eventual consistency, background-job cadence, delayed policy enforcement, catalog refresh requirements, and grace periods before cleanup really lands.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n/Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-signal-radar-runner/logs/iteration_008.log:21:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_9\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,240p' ../memory/CONTEXT.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Theme Signal Radar Context\\n\\n## Fact\\n\\n- Shared workspace:\\n  - `workspace/theme-exploration-shared` points to `/Users/lifcc/Desktop/code/AI/research/theme-exploration-shared`.\\n  - Write output only to `signals/`.\\n- Signal standard:\\n  - Separate facts, inferences, and recommendations.\\n  - Preserve source URLs for every factual claim.\\n  - Prefer primary or near-primary sources.\\n  - Mark confidence as high, medium, or low.\\n  - Do not invent missing facts; weak sourcing requires an evidence-gap note.\\n- 2026-05-04: created `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-04-signal-radar-batch-001.md` with 31 source-backed signals across AI agents, coding agents, AI devtools, AI infra/pricing, creative AI, local-first tools, open-source productization, and content automation.\\n- 2026-05-04: created `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-05-signal-radar-batch-002.md` with 12 protocol/distribution signals on MCP, A2A, ACP, managed endpoints, registry surfaces, and IDE support.\\n- 2026-05-04: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-06-signal-radar-batch-003.md` with 10 control-plane signals across approvals, auth, quotas, sandboxing, registry trust, and tool-surface minimization.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-07-signal-radar-batch-004.md` with 9 observability/accountability signals across traces, eval loops, compliance logs, usage metering, session logs, and post-action review.\\n- 2026-05-05: created queued file `theme-exploration-shared/signals/2026-05-08-signal-radar-batch-005.md` with 9 change-control/provenance signals across frozen snapshots, action diffs, model pinning, immutable revisions, signed attestations, verified catalogs, and plugin signing/review.\\n-